# ⚛️ React

Follow the **programming** and **typescript** rules. This rule adds React-specific conventions only.

---

## 📋 General principles

- **One component per file** — each component lives in its own file; do not put multiple component definitions in one
  file.
- **Always export the props type** — the type of a component's props must be exported so it can be reused (e.g. by state
  hooks or parents).
- **Props type naming** — always name the component's props type `<ComponentName>Props` (e.g. `ButtonProps` for
  `Button`, `InputViewProps` for `InputView`).
- **Wrappers: inherit the child’s props, don’t copy them by hand** — when your component mostly passes props through to
  another component (same DOM or child UI):
  - **Do:** build your props type from the child’s exported props (`InnerProps`), drop only what you replace yourself
    (often `children`, layout/class names), add your own fields, then pass the rest to the child:
    `type WrapperProps = Omit<InnerProps, 'children' | 'className'> & { label: string }` and
    `<Child {...innerProps} />`.
  - **Don’t:** list the same props again (`disabled`, `onClick`, …) on the wrapper — they drift from the child and every
    new child prop needs manual updates everywhere.
  - **Why:** the child API grows (new optional props) and wrappers keep working without edits.
- **Hooks in `hooks` directory** — all hook modules (files that export React hooks) must live in a directory named
  `hooks` (e.g. `hooks/useFormState.ts`, `app/core/hooks/useFormState.ts`). Hook file names use camelCase (see
  TypeScript rule).
- **`cn` instead of `className` in props** — for component props use the name `cn` (not `className`), and compose class
  names via `_.cn(...)` instead of template strings or manual concatenation.
